                                                                                                               Special satellite   for navy 
          SUJAN DUTTA                                    
	New Delhi, Oct. 22: The Indian Navy is to get its own satellite with a footprint across the Indian Ocean region. The satellite is to be launched next year.        
	The Naval Communications Satellite figured in discussions of senior navy officers conference here today when defence minister A.K. Antony said it will significantly improve connectivity.         
	A navy officer said the service was looking at the satellite, to be launched by Isro, not as a military satellite but as a communications satellite. Dedicated satellites for the air force and the army will follow.        
	The communications satellite will be at the heart of the network-centric operations that the navy is charting. The geo-stationary satellite will have a footprint between 600 nautical miles (around 1,110km) and 1,000 nautical miles (around 1,850km). The navy views the Indian Ocean region from the Persian Gulf to the Straits of Malacca as its area of strategic responsibility.        
	The officer said all Indian naval platforms  ships, aircraft and shore establishments  would be data-linked through the satellite.                                                                                                                                                                            
